Import Data

  • Store the credit card data in a variable
  • Since the response variable is categorical, we change the data type from int to factor
cc_data <- read.csv("creditcard.csv", header = T, sep = ",")
#str(cc_data)

cc_data <- cc_data %>%
  mutate(Class = as.factor(Class))

Check for Class Imbalance

  • We need to check if our data is balanced or unbalanced
  • We notice that the fraud data is a minority class (17.27%)
class_0 <- table(cc_data$Class)[1]
class_1 <- table(cc_data$Class)[2]

#Data is highly unbalanced so we need to do some sort of sampling before running the algorithm
class_1*100/nrow(cc_data)

Correlation Matrix

  • Before we train our model we create a correlation matrix
  • The matrix helps us find if there are any predictors that are correlated with each other
  • If there are predictors that are correlated then we would consider only one of them as a predictor
correlated <- cor(cc_data[,1:30])
corrplot(correlated, method = "circle")

Feature Scaling

  • In some machine learning algorithms, if the range of values for a variable vary too much, the objective functions of the algorithm will not work well with the data and our results will be incorrect
  • We leverage the preProcess function to transform the data such that we rescale the values to ensure that the mean is at 0 and the range of values for a variable are acceptable such that the objective functions can operate correctly
preprocessparams <- preProcess(cc_data_new[,1:30])

cc_data_final <- transformed
cc_data_final$Class <- cc_data$Class

cc_data_final <- cc_data_final %>%
  mutate(Class = as.factor(Class))

Split the data into training and validation

  • Now we split the data into a training set and a validation set with an 80-20 split
#Split into train and test
div <- sample(nrow(cc_data_final), 80 * nrow(cc_data_final)/100, replace = FALSE)
cc_data_train <- cc_data_final[div,]

SMOTE

  • Since our data set is unbalanced we will synthetically introduce minority class data and remove some of the majority class data by using the SMOTE technique
  • The other techniques that can be used are undersampling, oversampling and ROSE
smote_train <- SMOTE(Class ~ ., data  = cc_data_train, perc.over = 1000, perc.under = 200)                         
table(smote_train$Class)
## 
##    0    1 
## 8120 4466
table(cc_data_train$Class)
## 
##      0      1 
## 227439    406

K-Fold Cross Validation

  • Once our data is ready for training we can use the train control function to specify the cross validation technique
  • We use 10 fold cross validation which is repeated 5 times to ensure that our model trains well
  • By using 10 folds we split our training data into 10 equal folds such that the model trains on 9 folds at a time and tests on 1 fold
  • This is done until each fold is used by the model for testing the performance of the model
  • The above process is repeated 5 times
train_control <- trainControl(method = "repeatedcv", number = 10, repeats = 5)

Top Feature Selection

  • We can randomly select which features are good for our model by simply eyeballing but we can create a subset of variables by also using a random forest that gives us the features that we have used and their score
  • It is possible to use all the provided variables in the model but that is not ideal since we want to avoid overfitting
  • Include a variable in the model only if adding it improves the score significantly
model <- train(Class ~ ., method = "rf", data = smote_train)

Validation Set - Boosted Logistic Regression

  • Once we train our model we would like to validate its performance by predicting the results for our validation set
  • We already know the results for the set but would like to check our models performance for data that it has not seen before
  • Note that the threshold for our classifier is kept at 0.5 or 50%
  • We will discuss more on how changing the threshold of the classifier impacts our metrics
cc_data_validation <- cc_data_final[-div,]

cc_data_validation$predicted_val <- 
  ifelse(as.numeric(predict(model_new, type = "prob", newdata = cc_data_validation)[,2] >= 0.5),1,0)

Output Metrics - Boosted Logistic Regression

  • We create a confusion matrix that gives us the true positive, true negative, false positive and false negative values
  • Depending on the business question we can define which metric is important to us
  • Recall: Since our task is to find cases of fraud recall will be an important metric. As a business we would want to capture as many cases of fraud as possible. Even if it means we are accidentally classifying some customers as potential cases of fraud. The risk for the business is higher if someone who was fraudulant escaped us
  • Precision: This helps us capture cases where we are extremely sure that the potential cases of fraud are definitely going to happen. If our risk is losing customers and we are more concerned with catching cases where fraud will most definitely happen we prefer using precision as the metric. Note that in cases of unbalanced data sets such as the current example our precision will be extremely poor
  • Accuracy: We can identify how a classifier performs by correctly predicting true positives and true negatives correctly from all the total cases that are present. For an imbalanced dataset accuracy is not a good metric because even if the classifier predicts all the cases as the majority class our metric will still have a high value which is not a good indicator
  • F1 Score: A harmonic mean of precision and recall. Ideally for a model we would want a good balance between precision and recall and we can achieve that by looking at the F1 score of the classifier
  • ROC: An ROC curve is a plot that shows the tradeoff between sensitivity and specificity. The closer the curve to the left hand and top border, the better the model performance. The more the area under the curve (AUC) of the model, the better the model
  • PR Curve: Another alternative to F1 Score is a PR Curve. It helps to show how balanced the precision and recall are. Although for our current case, we are more concerned with getting a better recall score, for a more balanced scenario we would prefer having a PR Curve that gives us the threshold at which we have a stable value of precision and recall
  • We mentioned about the threshold of our classifier in the previous section. By default the threshold is 50%
  • We can make our model stricter, such that we have better precision by increasing the threshold to greater than 50%
  • We can also make our model lenient, that is, reduce the threshold to less than 50% to allow a better value for recall
  • Note that depending on the business question that needs to be answered we can vary the threshold to improve precision or recall. However, if we want a balanced model we should keep the threshold at 50%
conf_mat <- table(cc_data_validation$predicted_val, cc_data_validation$Class)

tn <- conf_mat[1]
fp <- conf_mat[2]
fn <- conf_mat[3]
tp <- conf_mat[4]


recall <- tp/(tp + fn)
precision <- tp/(tp + fp)
accuracy <- (tp + tn)/(tn + fp + fn + tp)
f1_score <- (2 * precision * recall)/(precision + recall)

Training Set - Boosted Logistic Regression

  • Since we performed feature selection by first leveraging a random forest, we only chose a subset of all the variables that were provided to us
  • In the below model we have used all the available variables to see if there is an improvement in the model by leveraging everything that is provided to us
  • If we check the output metrics of the below model with all variables, we see that there is a decrease values for all our metrics. We are overfitting the model and hence it is better to use features that are non correlated to each other as well as only features that impact the model significantly
model_new_full <- train(Class ~ ., method = "LogitBoost", data = smote_train)

Complex Models - SVM with Weights

  • Once we use the more generalized model, we then try to see if we can improve the model metrics further by using a more complex/flexible model
  • It is important to note that a more complex model will result in a better training result but the test error might be even higher if the model is overfitting. A complex model tends to fit closer to our training data and hence might even fit to the noise that is present in our data
  • Although a more generalized model does not give us perfect metrics, it is a much safer choice that we can consider with more confidence
  • This being said, a generalized model is not necessarily the solution every time as a simple line might not be the best classifier. We might indeed need a more flexible model in certain cases

Conclusion

  • We can see that even though we are using more complex/flexible models, our output metrics are not improving significantly
  • We need to collect more data as well as find new features that would help improve our precision significantly as well
  • With the current data we have a good recall that enables us to classify a high percentage of potential fraudsters successfully
  • However, since our precision is extremely low, we are also accidentally classifying clients that are not fraudulent as prone to committing a fraud which poses the problem of us losing clients
